</div><footer class="entry-footer"></footer></article><article class="post-1052 post type-post status-publish format-standard category-noteworthy-acheivement entry" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/CreativeWork"><header class="entry-header"><h1 class="entry-title" itemprop="headline"><a href="https://www.stat.uci.edu/knowable-magazine-when-courtroom-science-goes-wrong-and-how-stats-can-fix-it-hal-stern-featured/" rel="bookmark">Knowable Magazine: &#8220;When courtroom science goes wrong â€” and how stats can fix it&#8221; (Hal Stern featured)</a></h1> 
<p class="entry-meta"><time class="entry-time" itemprop="datePublished" datetime="2018-10-15T13:10:09+00:00">October 15, 2018</time> </p></header><div class="entry-content" itemprop="text"><p><img class="alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-1059" src="http://www.stat.uci.edu/wp-content/stat/uploads/Hal-Stern-Knowable-Magazine-comic-Likelihood-Ratio-150x150.png" alt="" width="150" height="150" srcset="https://www.stat.uci.edu/wp-content/stat/uploads/Hal-Stern-Knowable-Magazine-comic-Likelihood-Ratio-150x150.png 150w, https://www.stat.uci.edu/wp-content/stat/uploads/Hal-Stern-Knowable-Magazine-comic-Likelihood-Ratio-300x300.png 300w, https://www.stat.uci.edu/wp-content/stat/uploads/Hal-Stern-Knowable-Magazine-comic-Likelihood-Ratio.png 430w" sizes="(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px" />Bite marks, shoe prints, crime-scene fibers: Matches to suspects are often far shakier than courtroom experts claim. Better statistical methods â€” among them, a little beast known as the â€œlikelihood ratioâ€ â€” can cut down on wrong convictions.</p>
